**F1 — `tx.preview()` does not exist, and is nearly free to add.** `Transaction::new` builds `working: Graph<C>` as a full clone of the graph (`transaction.rs:38`). Every staging and recompute step runs against `self.working`. The real graph is untouched until the *very last line* of `commit()`: `std::mem::swap(self.graph, &mut self.working)` (`transaction.rs:285`). `Drop` just clears `transaction_open` (`transaction.rs:302`) — a dropped, uncommitted transaction discards the working copy cleanly. **So a dry run is: run the commit pipeline, build the `TransactionResult`, and return it *without the swap*.** The clone is already paid. There is no `preview`/`dry_run` in the tree today (grep-confirmed). This is real, small, and the keystone the first design missed — it is upstream ask #1. [...] impl<'graph, C: Clone + PartialEq> Transaction<'graph, C> {
    /// Runs the full commit pipeline on the working copy and returns the
    /// TransactionResult WITHOUT writing back to the graph. The transaction is
    /// consumed; the real graph is untouched. Nearly free — the working clone
    /// is already paid at `begin_transaction`.
    pub fn preview(mut self) -> GraphResult<TransactionResult<C>>;
}
```

Implementation is `commit()` minus the final `std::mem::swap` and minus mutating the *real* graph's audit state (record audit onto `working` so the returned result carries explanations, then drop `working`). ~30 lines, reusing the existing pipeline. I will draft this PR against `~/src/trellis` and its test (`preview_does_not_mutate_graph`, `preview_result_equals_commit_result_then_discard`) as the opening move — it is the cleanest possible "tenex-edge feeds Trellis" artifact. [...] ## Extraction approach
A clean equal-split, no surprises. I factored the shared pre-swap pipeline out of `commit()` into a private `fn run_pipeline(&mut self) -> GraphResult<(TransactionResult<C>, Vec<ScopeId>)>`. `run_pipeline` runs the entire pipeline on `self.working` (recompute, structural diffs, resource plans, output frames) and ends at `self.working.record_transaction_audit(...)`, returning `(result, closed_scopes)`. The audit is recorded onto `working` only — verified by reading; it never touches `self.graph`.

`commit()`'s **only** post-pipeline real-graph work was exactly three steps, which I moved verbatim into `commit`:
```rust
let (result, closed_scopes) = self.run_pipeline()?;
self.working.reclaim_closed_scopes(&closed_scopes);
std::mem::swap(self.graph, &mut self.working);
self.close();
Ok(result)
```
There were **no** post-pipeline real-graph mutations beyond the swap (reclaim runs on `working` before the swap), so `commit()` is behavior byte-identical. `preview(mut self)` = `run_pipeline()` then `Ok(result)` — no reclaim, no swap; `self`/`working` is dropped. [...] **Merged:** `tx.preview()` is in `pablof7z/trellis` master (squash `60e759d`, PR #164), issue #163 auto-closed, CI was green (format/lint/test/docs/bench + proptest/fuzz). The main Trellis checkout is fast-forwarded to include it. [...] 2. **`probe simulate <surface> --fact <InputFact-json>`** — stage a candidate fact, `preview()`, return the plan/frames/receipt as JSON, discard. This is "what happens if I commit this?" for agents — a Terraform-plan for a status/subscription change, answerable in-daemon in microseconds without touching the relay. [...] Meanwhile the build track kept moving: **`probe oracle / simulate / why / state` all landed green** (456 lib tests, +20). The essay's boldest line — *"the check that proves the engine honest ships inside the engine… so I can point it at the running system"* — is now literally true: `probe oracle` runs the full-recompute oracle against the live daemon graphs, and `probe simulate` dry-runs a fact via `tx.preview()` with a test proving the graph is untouched. Next I'll have a Fable agent stress-test whether the whole surface is genuinely useful/complete/real before I call the essay done.
